<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1919-09-25T09:44:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1919-09-25T09:44:00-05:00" n="483" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d483">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">882.77/31: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Liberia</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Bundy</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                    State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Monrovia</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1919-09-25T14:00:00-00:44"><hi rend="italic">September
                                            25, 1919, 2 p.m.</hi></date><lb/>[<hi rend="italic">Received September 26, 12.42 a.m.</hi>]</dateline></opener>
                            <p>President of Liberia has handed me a copy of the application of the
                                Liberian International Corporation of London for a comprehensive
                                railway concession in the Republic. This application which is an
                                entirely new scheme has just been filed in Liberian State Department
                                and will come before Legislature in December.</p>
                            <p>Liberian International Corporation as [<hi rend="italic">is?</hi>]
                                understood to be same financial group in whose interest Sir Alfred
                                Sharpe visited Liberia last year. Copy of application will be sent
                                Department by next mail.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Bundy</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>